INFLUENZA (25): EUROPE
*********************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

In this update:
[1] Europe
[2] UK

******
[1] Europe
Date: Thu 30 Dec 2010
Source: EuroFlu Bulletin 51/2010 [edited]
<http://www.euroflu.org/cgi-files/bulletin_v2.cgi>


- This issue is based on data reported in week 51/2010 by 42 Member
States in the WHO European Region.
- Influenza activity remains low in most countries, but influenza
virus detections are increasing.
- 34 percent of sentinel specimens tested positive for influenza.
- Pandemic influenza A(H1N1) 2009, influenza B and influenza A(H3N2)
viruses are circulating in the Region.

Current situation - week 51/2010
--------------------------------
Increasing consultation rates were reported by 8 of the 32 countries
submitting data on influenza-like illness (ILI) or acute respiratory
infection (ARI), mostly in children aged 0-4 years. Of the 9 countries
presenting calculated baseline thresholds, France, Israel, the Russian
Federation and Ukraine reported clinical consultation rates above
their thresholds. Of the 31 countries reporting on the geographical
spread of influenza, most reported either no (7) or sporadic (12)
activity, while 6 reported local, 2 regional and 4 widespread
activity. The impact of influenza on health care systems was low in 17
of the 18 countries reporting on this indicator, with Israel reporting
moderate impact. Respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) is also
circulating, and 15 countries reported detections during week 51.

Virological situation - week 51/2010
-----------------------------------
Sentinel physicians collected 906 respiratory specimens, of which 309
(34 percent) were positive for influenza virus: 212 (69 percent) were
influenza A and 97 (31 percent) were influenza B. Of the influenza A
viruses, 165 were subtyped: 133 (81 percent) as pandemic A(H1) and 32
(19 percent) as A(H3). For the 16 countries testing 20 or more
sentinel specimens, influenza positivity ranged from 0 percent to 80
percent, with a median of 28 percent (mean: 30 percent). Influenza
positivity was highest in Belgium (80 percent), Finland (61 percent),
and Israel (50 percent). Among specimens tested from non-sentinel
sources, 698 were positive for influenza: 433 (62 percent) influenza A
and 265 (38 percent) influenza B. Of the influenza A viruses, 339 were
subtyped: 320 (94 percent) as pandemic A(H1) and 19 (6 percent) as
A(H3).

Since week 40/2010, 182 influenza viruses have been characterized
antigenically: 97 were A(H1) pandemic A/California/7/2009 (H1N1)-like;
25 were A(H3) A/Perth/16/2009 (H3N2)-like; 6 were B/Florida/4/2006-
like (B/Yamagata/16/88 lineage); and 54 were B/Brisbane/60/2008-like
(B/Victoria/2/87 lineage). Based on the genetic characterization of 39
influenza viruses, 27 belonged to the pandemic A/California/7/2009
A(H1N1) clade; 3 belonged to the A(H3) clade represented by A/Perth/
16/2009; 4 belonged to the A(H3) clade represented by the A/Victoria/
208/2009 - A/Hong Kong/2121/2010 subgroup; 4 belonged to the B/
Bangladesh/3333/2007 clade (Yamagata) lineage; and one to the
B/Florida/ 4/2006 clade (Yamagata) lineage.

Cumulative virological update - weeks 40-51/2010
------------------------------------------------
A total of 3927 influenza virus detections have been reported, of
which 2541 (65 percent) were influenza A and 1386 (35 percent)
influenza B. Of the influenza A viruses, 1580 have been subtyped: 1362
(86 percent) as pandemic influenza A(H1); 217 (14 percent) as
influenza A(H3); and one (under one percent) as influenza A(H1) [not
pandemic].

Comment
-------
Overall, influenza activity remains low in most countries of the WHO
European Region. In week 51/2010, 34 percent of sentinel samples
tested positive for influenza compared with 39 percent in the previous
week. This apparent drop in positivity probably relates to fewer
consultations and/or lower reporting of data owing to the Christmas
and New Year holidays. This interpretation is supported by the facts
that the number of countries reporting influenza detections and the
rates of positivity in sentinel samples observed in individual
countries are increasing. Pandemic A(H1N1) 2009, influenza type B, and
influenza A(H3) viruses have all been detected, and RSV [respiratory
syncytial virus] continues to circulate.

--
