******
[2] UK
Date: Thu 30 Dec 2010
Source: Health Protection Agency (HPA) Weekly National Influenza
Report - week 52 (2010) [edited]
<http://www.hpa.org.uk/web/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1287147913271>


Influenza activity continues to increase across the UK. GP [general
practitioner] consultation rates are now above baseline levels in all
4 countries [England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland]. Influenza
A H1N1 (2009) and B are the predominant circulating viruses with few,
sporadic A (H3N2) viruses detected. The H1N1 (2009) virus strain is
virologically and epidemiologically similar to that seen during the
pandemic. The virus strains circulating are overall well matched to
the current influenza vaccine. The HPA expects to see continued
elevated influenza activity for several weeks.

In week 51 (ending 26 Dec 2010), the weekly ILI [influenza-like
illness] consultation rates increased across the UK. Weekly influenza
ILI consultation rates remain above baseline levels in England (124.4
per 100 000) and Wales (92.1 per 100 000). The rates have now
increased above the baseline in Scotland (58.4 per 100 000) and
Northern Ireland (99.4 per 100 000).

The weekly national proportion of NHS Direct cold/flu calls for week
51 has increased; however, the daily proportion has decreased slightly
to 10.4 percent on 28 Dec 2010, from a peak of 12.9 percent on 21 Dec
2010. The proportion of calls for fever in the 5-14 year age group
decreased from 21.6 percent to 16.8 percent, though this remains above
the baseline level of 9 percent. This suggests the possibility that we
may be approaching the peak of influenza activity.

Two acute respiratory disease outbreaks were reported in UK in week
51, one in a primary school and one in a prison. This brings the total
reported this season so far to 122. It should be noted that most
schools across the UK were on holiday in week 51.

126 of 189 (66.7 percent) specimens from patients with ILI presenting
to sentinel GPs in England in week 51 were reported as positive for
influenza. The proportion of specimens reported to DataMart (England)
as positive for influenza has increased to 43.2 percent (1711 of
3959). The proportion of samples positive for RSV [respiratory
syncytial virus] and rhinovirus is stable or decreasing.

Currently, the main circulating influenza strains are influenza A
(H1N1) and influenza B. From week 36, 39 deaths associated with
influenza infection have been reported. The majority of fatal cases
reported were unimmunised. By week 50, the proportion of people in
England aged over 65 years who had received the 2010/11 influenza
vaccine was 68.5 percent. For those in a risk group aged under 65 it
was 43.0 percent.

On 21 Dec 2010, the UK Department of Health issued a letter to NHS
staff in England to inform them that the use of antiviral drugs is
recommended for treatment of influenza in high risk patients. In
Europe, most countries are starting to report early influenza
activity. In the USA and Canada, overall influenza activity has
increased.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Map of UK at:
<http://www.maps-of-britain.co.uk/large-political-britain-map.htm> - Mod.JW]

[These data put the current situation in Europe in perspective and may
help to dispel some of the more alarmist speculations currently in
circulation. The influenza outbreak in Europe is following the normal
seasonal pattern, and the seasonal vaccine seems well-matched to the
current epidemic strains. However, the level of protective vaccination
in the population of some countries is less than desirable - Mod.CP]
